Before Kenya reported its first confirmed case of Covid-19 on March 12, the 2020 tennis calendar was rolling. 

The year started with the eight-team East African Tennis Championships at the Gymkhana Club in Dar es Salaam. Tanzania Tennis Federation hosted teams from Kenya, Rwanda, Seychelles, Somalia, Uganda, Tanzania, Burundi and Comoros. 

Kenya’s top female player Angela Okutoyi, 16, who is currently ranked 271 in the ITF Junior Rankings,her twin sister Roselida Asumwa and Alicia Owegi represented the country in girls’ under-16 category, with Brandon Isami, Raymond Oduor and Edmond Ogega playing in boys’ category. 











Kenya's Angela Okutoyi plays a forehand shot against Alicia Owegi during their Britam Kenya Open Tennis Championship semi-final match on September 21, 2018 at Nairobi Club.
Photo credit: File | Nation Media Group

 

Liberty Kibue, Ruinclife Ominde and Gilbert Wechuli played in boys’ under-14 category. 

Kenya wound up fourth in the championship with two points. In the boys’ under-16 category, Kenya beat both Seychelles and Eritrea 3-0, but fell 2-1 to Burundi. 

Kenya also beat Uganda 2-1 and Seychelles 3-0 in boys’ 14 and under category, but the team suffered a 3-0 defeat in the hands of Rwanda and also suffered 2-1 losses to both Burundi and hosts Tanzania. 

There was something to cheer about when Kenyan girls finished first in both girls’ under-14 and under-16 categories in the 10-day competition. The team thrashed Uganda 2-0 and Tanzania 3-0 in the final of girls’ team event to finish top with two points. 



