Uganda and Tanzania finished second and third in the category. At the championship, Kenya Under-14 team posted similar results, the country returning an impressive 3-0 victory against Tanzania, Burundi and Comoros to bring the team's points tally to three. 

The team qualified for the Africa Junior Championships which had been scheduled to be held in Togo in June before Covid-19 struck. Morocco, Tunisia, Algeria and Nigeria were the teams to watch. 

In February, Kenya hosted the African qualifiers for BNP World Team Cup Africa. The women’s team comprised of Kenya wheelchair tennis team captain Jane Ndenga, Phoebe Masika and Veronica Osogo and Asiya Mohammed, while the men’s team featured Lawrence Karanja, Collins Odhiambo, Peter Munuve and Rajab Abdallah. 






 Kenya's women wheelchair tennis chairperson Jane Ndenga returns a lower forehand during the 2018 World Cup in Apeldoorn in the Netherlands.
Photo credit: Pool | Nation Media Group

 

Kenyan men played in Pool A of the tournament alongside South Africa, Tanzania and Cameroon while Morocco, Nigeria, Ghana and Egypt were in Pool B. Kenyan women were in Pool B alongside Ghana and Cameroon, while Morocco, Tanzania and Egypt featured in Pool A. 

Kenya women’s team finished second behind Morocco but ahead of third-placed Ghana in the tournament, while Egypt, Tanzania and Cameroon finished in that order respectively to miss out on a chance to play in the World Cup. 



