Kenya finished fifth in the men’s category, while South Africa, Morocco, Nigeria and Tanzania took the first four positions, followed by Ghana, Cameroon and Egypt respectively. 






South Africa (men) and Morocco (women) qualified to represent Africa in the World Cup that had been scheduled for Portugal from April 30 to May 6. It was the second time Morocco women’s team qualified for the World Cup, and the third time for South Africa's men's team. 

To improve the standards of the game locally, Tennis Kenya launched junior wheelchair development programme in Masaku School for the Physically Challenged in Machakos County early this year, and at Joytown School in Thika. 

Before Covid-19 disrupted sports globally, the Kenyan Davis Cup team of Ismael Changawa, Ibrahim Kibet, Kevin Cheruiyot and Sheil Kotacha was due to compete in the Euro/Africa Group Two play-offs. 

The team had been placed in Pool B of alongside Tunisia, Costa Rica, Poland, Syria, Greece, Jamaica, Puerto Rico, Estonia, Vietnam, Sri Lanka and Latvia. 

The 12 teams qualified for the competition from Africa Group Three play-offs held last year. Kenya qualified for the Euro/Africa playoffs after beating Mozambique 2-0 to top Pool A in Africa Group Three play-offs last year. 



