Last month, the first tennis tournament was held in Kenya after almost nine months of inactivity. 

The first of an eight series tournament featuring both men and women saw some of Kenya's top senior talents turn up to compete at Nairobi Club. The tournaments ran from November 23 to December 6. 

'Better season' 

Officials are looking forward to a better season starting January. 

"Staying away from the courts has been a big disappointment for us because we had plans for an exciting year full events to expose our players to competitions, especially the juniors who doubled in number in 2019," said Tennis Kenya President James Kenani. 

"We hope to recover the time we have lost from January, and to make a statement in June during the Billy Jean King Cup (previously known as FED Cup). 

“We are also excited that we might have some of our players contest in the Australian Open but we will know the full details by end of January," he added. 

Tennis Kenya Executive Officer Nancy Nduku is optimistic that the federation will host three international events in January, including ITF East Africa Junior Circuit, 10th Nairobi International Junior Circuit and the 12th Kenya International Junior Circuit. 

